# <type>(<scope>): <summary>                        # max 72 chars
#
# <body — wrap at 72, explain WHY, not WHAT>
#
# <footer — e.g. "Closes #123", "BREAKING CHANGE: ...">
#
# --- Conventional Commits cheat sheet ---
# type:
#   feat      new feature
#   fix       bug fix
#   chore     tooling / maintenance
#   docs      documentation only
#   refactor  code change that neither fixes nor adds
#   test      adding or updating tests
#   perf      performance improvement
#   build     build system / deps
#   ci        CI / workflow
#
# scope:       optional — the module or area touched (e.g. auth, wiki, ci)
# summary:     imperative, lowercase, no trailing period
# body:        prose; reference the WHY
# footer:      BREAKING CHANGE: ... or issue refs
#
# Wire this template once:  git config commit.template .gitmessage
#
# Wiki reminder:
# If this change touches a contract (port signature, invariant, security rule),
# also update the relevant docs/wiki/*.md AND add an entry to docs/wiki/log.md.
# The pre-commit hook will block the commit if you forget — that's the signal
# to pause and check whether a wiki update is genuinely needed.
